### PHP Exception Handling

Exceptions are an object-oriented way to handle errors in PHP.

### Exception Class

```php
<?php
throw new Exception("Something went wrong");
?>
```

### The Exception Class

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `getMessage()` | Get error message |
| `getCode()` | Get error code |
| `getFile()` | Get filename where exception occurred |
| `getLine()` | Get line number |
| `getTrace()` | Get stack trace as array |
| `getTraceAsString()` | Get stack trace as string |

### Throwing Exceptions

```php
<?php
function divide($a, $b) {
    if ($b == 0) {
        throw new Exception("Division by zero");
    }
    return $a / $b;
}

// This will cause an uncaught exception
echo divide(10, 0);
?>
```

### Custom Exception Class

```php
<?php
class MathException extends Exception {
    public function errorMessage() {
        return "Math Error: " . $this->getMessage();
    }
}

throw new MathException("Invalid operation");
?>
```

### Errors vs Exceptions

| Feature | Error | Exception |
|---------|-------|------------|
| Handling | `set_error_handler()` | `try/catch` |
| Control | Cannot be caught easily | Can be caught and handled |
| OOP | Procedural | Object-oriented |
| Stack trace | Limited | Full stack trace |

> **Key Point:** Exceptions should be used for exceptional conditions that you want to handle gracefully, while traditional errors are for PHP-level issues.
